<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="ch-irrational-numbers" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Irrational Numbers</title>

  <introduction>
    
    <p>
      <term>Rational numbers:</term>
      These are numbers that can be expressed as a simple fraction of two integers.These include whole numbers, fractions and terminating or recurring decimals. However, as the 
      ancient Greeks famously discovered, the number line contains gaps that rational 
      numbers cannot fill.
    </p>
    <p>
      The “gaps” on the number line that cannot be filled by rational numbers are 
    occupied by <term>irrational numbers</term> These numbers complete the number line, ensuring 
    that every point corresponds to a real number.
    </p>
    <p>
      <term>Irrational numbers:</term>. These are numbers 
      that cannot be written as a fraction <m>\frac{a}{b}</m>, and when expressed as 
      decimals, they continue forever without repeating a pattern. We will learn how 
      to identify these unique values, perform algebraic operations with radicals, 
      and understand why constants like <m>\pi</m> and <m>\sqrt{2}</m> are essential 
      for describing the world around us.
    </p>
 
  </introduction>

